Name: Murkowski, Lisa
text:
A few hours ago, a magnitude 7.3 earthquake struck off the Alaska Peninsula, just south of Sand Point. Local residents and summer visitors alike were able to evacuate thanks to federal tsunami advisories relayed through local public broadcasting stations.

That’s the real world. But here in the U.S. Senate, we are currently debating a rescissions package that would severely cut funding for the Corporation for Public Broadcasting, drastically affecting Alaska’s 27 public media stations and many more across the nation. 

Some colleagues claim they are targeting “radical leftist organizations” with these cuts, but in Alaska, these are simply organizations dedicated to their communities. Their response to today’s earthquake is a perfect example of the incredible public service these stations provide. They deliver local news, weather updates, and, yes, emergency alerts that save human lives. 

I want to thank KMXT in Kodiak, KUCB in Unalaska, and KSDP in Sand Point for giving Alaskans real-time updates and keeping us safe. 

The tsunami warnings are now thankfully canceled, but the warning to the U.S. Senate remains in effect. Today of all days, we should vote down these misguided cuts to public broadcasting.

Name: Sewell, Terri A.
text:
It is hard to believe that five years have passed since we lost John. He would have a lot to say about what’s going on these days. The attacks on our democracy. The whitewashing of our history. The efforts to make it harder for Americans to vote.

Old battles have indeed become new again, but if there is one thing that John taught us, it’s that we must press on!

When I am at my most distraught, I think about John's words as he crossed the Edmund Pettus Bridge for the last time before his passing. His body was frail and riddled with cancer but his mind was sharp and his charge to us was clear.

“Never give up. Never give in. Keep the faith, and keep your eyes on the prize.”

My friends, we are living through troubling times. We can be tired. We can be frustrated. We can be downright mad. But what we cannot do is give up.

Just imagine where we would be if John Lewis and those Foot Soldiers had given up on Bloody Sunday. They were beaten, bruised, gassed, and whipped. They had every reason to throw up their hands and surrender!

But they didn't. They got back up and tried again. They marched on until victory was won.

Now more than ever, we need to take a page from their playbook.

As we navigate this dark chapter of our history, let’s keep the faith, and let’s continue to get into some Good Trouble.

For John, and the nation he so loved. 💕

Name: Salazar, Maria Elvira
text:
This is incorrect.

This is a provision from the Dream Act included in the bill. No criminals or gang members are eligible. Period. 

Here’s how it works — when a Dreamer would apply to adjust status, there is an investigation - including a criminal background check, check for gang affiliation, and more. 

During that investigation, the federal and state gang database network can absolutely be a factor in determining gang membership, but the presence on a list alone does not disqualify them immediately.

There must be another factor to prove gang membership - which could be a criminal charge (not just conviction), tattoos, gang dress, evidence from law enforcement investigations, social media, witness testimony, prison records, etc. 

Also, the burden is on the Dreamer to prove they qualify for adjusted status - so if they are on a database (or not on a database, but there is other proof of gang membership), they have to prove that is incorrect. 

This is because the gang databases have proven inaccurate in federal courts.

That’s it - simple. Not a smoking gun.

Name: Loudermilk, Barry
text:
MYTH: NPR/PBS provide unbiased, quality news coverage.

FACT: While the broadcasters are statutorily required to ensure “strict adherence to objectivity and balance in all programs or series of programs of a controversial nature” (47 U.S.C. § 396(g)(1)(D)), they have never complied with that legal obligation. Instead, they have flouted the law, going out of their way to produce news media that is favorable to left-leaning politicians and institutions. For this reason alone, NPR and PBS should be deprived of federal funding.

According to an MRC report, recent examples include:
PBS:
1. 162 references to “far right” vs only 6 references to “far left”
2. 6 times as many liberal political guests as conservative guests
3. 88% positive coverage of the DNC vs 72% negative coverage of the RNC

NPR:
1. Banned coverage of the Hunter Biden laptop story, claiming it was a “mere distraction”
2. Bans diversity of thought on climate-change issues
3. Consistently cites Hamas propaganda and demonizes Israel

Name: Loudermilk, Barry
text:
MYTH: There are “local news” deserts that only NPR can fill.

FACT: 96% of Americans report using the internet regularly, providing far more access to news than ever before. In addition, Starlink can reach people in remote areas far more cheaply than broadcasters can. It is easier than ever before for Americans to find news via the internet, and to come to their own conclusions about the news they’re reading, rather than having that information dictated to them by biased NPR reporters.

Name: Loudermilk, Barry
text:
MYTH: Less than 1% of their operating funds come directly from taxpayers.

FACT: NPR/PBS refuse to provide data showing how much they collect in tax revenues (federal and state). However, they operate a legalized “kick-back” scheme, taking federal and state tax dollars from local affiliates for programming.

Name: Durbin, Richard J.
text:
Today’s Committee executive business meeting included 10 nominees—among them Emil Bove, nominated for a lifetime appointment on the federal bench.

Mr. Bove belongs nowhere near the federal bench.

He led the Administration’s effort to strike a corrupt bargain with New York City Mayor Eric Adams and has been trailed by a history of complaints—long predating his affiliation with President Trump—about his temperament, poor judgment, and lack of candor before the court.

Additionally, Erez Reuveni, a career Justice Department attorney who defended the first Trump Administration’s immigration policies, filed a whistleblower complaint with my office regarding Mr. Bove.

That complaint recounted that Mr. Bove suggested DOJ might need to say "f--- you" to federal courts that issued orders that the Administration opposed.

I asked Mr. Reuveni whether he could substantiate his claims, and in response, he provided text messages, email exchanges, and other documents corroborating his allegations.

Given Mr. Reuveni’s credible allegations against Mr. Bove, which, if true, clearly disqualify him for a lifetime appointment to the federal bench, I called for the Committee to hear from Mr. Reuveni, under oath, before we voted on Mr. Bove’s nomination.

But Chairman Grassley denied that request.

And today, he cut off debate time on Mr. Bove’s nomination before turning to his vote, as well as nine other nominations, including Ms. Pirro’s.

Chairman Grassley claimed that he was following Committee precedent. This is simply untrue.

When I was Chair, I only limited debate when Republicans invoked Senate rules to shut down Committee meetings, and after Committee members were given ample opportunities to voice their concerns about nominees on the agenda.

Today, Chairman Grassley blocked Democratic members from discussing the controversial records of nominees like Emil Bove and Jeanine Pirro, shut down debate, and forced votes for no apparent reason.

My question is this: what are my Senate Republican colleagues trying to hide?

Name: Cuellar, Henry
text:
Today I took a moment to pray and reflect in the Congressional Prayer Room. It’s a quiet space near the Capitol rotunda, set aside in 1955 for Members of Congress to seek spiritual guidance.

The stained glass window shows George Washington in prayer, surrounded by the powerful words from Lincoln’s Gettysburg address, “This Nation Under God,” as well as Psalm 16:1. These symbols reflect the faith that has guided our nation through every chapter of its history.

As a Catholic, I pray daily to guide my decisions, shape my values, and ground my work on behalf of the people I serve. I’m deeply grateful for this spiritual refuge in the Capitol, where faith meets duty.

May God bless our families.
May God bless our communities.
And may God bless the United States of America.

text: 3/ PBS children’s programming like Daniel Tiger’s Neighborhood, Sesame Street, Super Why, and Peg + Cat have decades of rigorous research proving their positive impact on early childhood development.

Name: Jackson, Jonathan L.
text: 2/ Public broadcasting is not just TV or radio. It is a lifeline. During extreme weather events and emergencies, public broadcasters provide critical safety information that can save lives. Cutting this funding puts public safety at serious risk.

Name: Jackson, Jonathan L.
text: 4/ A UCLA study found nearly 75% of teens who watched Daniel Tiger remember its social-emotional lessons years later—skills like managing emotions and problem solving that shape healthy adults.

Name: Jackson, Jonathan L.
text: 5/ Sesame Street viewers perform better on standardized tests for literacy, math, and vocabulary. It fosters pro-social behaviors like sharing and cooperation, helping kids succeed academically and socially.

Name: Jackson, Jonathan L.
text: 6/ These programs are especially crucial for low-income families and rural communities who rely heavily on public broadcasting for educational resources that are not accessible elsewhere.

Name: Jackson, Jonathan L.
text: 7/ Globally, Sesame Street has helped children in more than 15 countries learn literacy, numeracy, science, health, and safety, demonstrating the broad proven impact of public broadcasting beyond our borders.

Name: Jackson, Jonathan L.
text: 8/ Cutting $1 billion from public broadcasting funding is not just an attack on education—it is an attack on equity, public safety, and the right to reliable information.

Name: Jackson, Jonathan L.
text: 9/ As the House prepares to vote, know this: slashing funds for public broadcasting will hurt kids, endanger lives during emergencies, and silence reliable voices in rural America.

Name: Trahan, Lori
text:
Crypto is here to stay. That’s why we can’t afford to wait any longer to establish guardrails that protect consumers and bring long-overdue transparency to this rapidly evolving industry.
 
I voted YES on the GENIUS Act because it’s a meaningful step toward ensuring that Americans who choose to invest in stablecoins are protected from fraud and abuse. This bill is far from perfect and more must be done to confront the blatant corruption we’re seeing from Donald Trump, who has shamelessly used his position as President to line his pockets with millions in crypto. I’ll keep fighting for strong anti-corruption legislation to stop the kind of self-dealing that’s happening in plain sight.
 
I voted NO on the CLARITY Act. I support a regulatory framework that distinguishes between digital assets, fosters innovation, and promotes responsible growth, but this bill simply doesn’t get us there. It’s riddled with loopholes and carveouts that leave everyday investors exposed to the kinds of volatile, often fraudulent crypto schemes we’ve seen too regularly with memecoins. It fails to strike the right balance between innovation and consumer protection. As the bill moves to the Senate, it’s critical that our colleagues strengthen it, starting with ensuring that states like Massachusetts retain the authority to crack down on fraud and abuse.
 
I believe we can support innovation in the crypto space while standing firmly against the predatory practices that have taken root in the absence of meaningful oversight. The future of digital assets should be built on transparency, accountability, and protections for everyday investors. That’s the balance I’ll keep fighting for.

Name: Cruz, Ted
text:
My meeting with Secretary of the Army Daniel Driscoll focused on the Army Transformation Initiative (ATI) and the vital, strategic role Texas plays in advancing the Army’s modernization goals.

Given the Army presence at the Corpus Christi and Red River Army Depots, Army Futures Command, Forts Hood and Bliss, Joint Base San Antonio and other critical military installations, it’s clear that Texas offers unmatched advantages in infrastructure, workforce, and geographic positioning. Texas is the most capable and ready state to accelerate Army transformation.

The conversation reinforced that Texas has long served as the backbone of American defense—home to hundreds of thousands of servicemembers, military families, and a robust defense industrial base. With world-class installations and proven readiness, Texas is uniquely positioned to lead the next era of the U.S. Army.

I affirmed that Texas should not just be a participant, but a core partner in what ATI represents: forward-leaning innovation, operational agility, and strategic readiness. The discussion highlighted the critical importance of protecting and expanding the missions at Red River Army Depot (RRAD), Joint Base San Antonio (JBSA), and Army Futures Command (AFC)—each of which plays an indispensable role in supporting the Army’s current and future force.

The meeting also included proposals to relocate additional Army missions and capabilities to Texas. These actions would strengthen ATI implementation while maximizing efficiency, speed, and national security outcomes.

This meeting reflects Texas’s continued leadership and commitment to ensuring the U.S. Army remains the most capable, modern, and ready force in the world - with Texas at its core.

Name: Brecheen, Josh
text:
Today I voted to advance the CBDC Anti-Surveillance State Act out of the House, in tandem with the GENIUS Act and the Clarity Act, which will ensure that there will never be a central bank digital currency created. The bills passed today will allow a cohesive and commonsense framework in which stablecoins (digital assets that are pegged to actual assets such as the USD) can be bought, sold, and traded similar to stocks, without being designated as securities. One important note, these stablecoins are not government run, created, or controlled–they are part of the free market and thus their use is not required. 

The passage of these three bills is yet another step forward in bringing forth the golden era that President Trump has promised and will provide regulatory clarity in the markets. 

Now that the House has passed the CBDC Anti-Surveillance State Act, it is the Senate’s responsibility to take it up and pass it. In the event that the Senate does not take it up, House Freedom Caucus, in coordination with White House and Leadership, was able to secure a commitment that anti-central bank digital currency language will be included in the National Defense Authorization Act, a ‘must pass’ bill that is advanced annually.

Name: Cuellar, Henry
text:
During today’s Appropriations markup, the committee adopted my amendment to the FY26 Transportation, Housing and Urban Development bill to prohibit civilian drones from airspace within one mile of the southern border.

Cartels are using drones to track Border Patrol and troop movements, enabling the smuggling of drugs, weapons, and people into the U.S. These systems are growing more advanced and harder to detect, putting border communities and law enforcement at serious risk. Unlike responsible operators, cartels don’t follow regulations — they adapt quickly to evade detection. This amendment helps our agents match that agility by giving them the tools and authority to respond in real time.

Working with @RepCloudTX, we developed bipartisan language that directs @FAANews, @DHSgov, and @CBP to create a no-drone zone along the southern border. It targets illegal activity without disrupting responsible drone use. The amendment also includes clear exceptions for law enforcement, emergency responders, and legal operators like farmers and ranchers.

This sends a clear message: Congress recognizes the threat and expects federal agencies to act swiftly to counter it.

I remain committed to securing the border, protecting our communities, and ensuring law enforcement has what it needs to get the job done. I thank Chairman @rep_stevewomack and Ranking Member @RepJamesClyburn for supporting this commonsense, bipartisan step to safeguard our homeland.

Name: Roy, Chip
text:
🚨Rep. Roy Statement on Votes on Digital Assets Legislation:

"Today, House Republicans took a significant step forward to provide a market framework to ensure that Americans can innovate with cryptocurrencies. 

I supported H.R. 3633, the CLARITY Act, to allow such innovation without fear of an uncertain regulatory environment.
 
I was most proud to support H.R. 1919, the Anti-CBDC Surveillance State Act – which will guarantee that Central Bank Digital Currencies (CBDC’s) are not permitted in the United States. CBDC’s would represent a radical attack on the privacy of Americans and would allow government and financial institutional unchecked power over our bank accounts, and importantly, our freedom to purchase and move about unimpeded by government surveillance. No government power should be able to limit the ability of a citizen to transact pre-emotive lay based on the policy whims of any particular party in power. The Senate should pass this and send it to the President’s desk immediately.
 
Regrettably, I opposed S. 1582, the GENIUS Act because it was passed without the necessary protections to prevent Central Bank Digital Currencies, and I do not believe we should proceed with building out the necessary structures for stable coin or the development of market structures (CLARITY) without the protection against CBDC.
 
Innovation and prosperity is important – but freedom is the centerpiece of both. We should demand freedom first."

Name: Trahan, Lori
text:
Public broadcasting isn’t just Big Bird and Sesame Street – it’s how families in Massachusetts and across the country get lifesaving emergency alerts, stay connected to their communities, and access trusted, educational programming. Slashing support for public radio and television will silence local newsrooms, especially in rural areas, and undermine the emergency broadcast systems we rely on in times of crisis.

We saw the consequences of weakened alert systems during the catastrophic floods in Texas. Communities were caught flat-footed, in part because they lacked access to timely, reliable emergency broadcasts. Contrast that with what we saw just yesterday in Alaska, where public broadcasters immediately issued alerts after a powerful 7.3 magnitude offshore earthquake, potentially saving lives. These two realities show exactly what’s at stake. If these cuts move forward, the Trump administration will be making a conscious choice to leave communities more vulnerable, more isolated, and less safe.

I voted no because I will always stand up for public safety, for local journalism, and for the families who depend on these vital services every single day.

Name: Greene, Marjorie Taylor
text:
This week Congress passed crypto legislation.

The American people hardly have any idea what it is, what it means, and what passed.

1. GENUIS ACT - I voted NO. It passed the Senate and the House and will be signed into law today. 
This bill regulates stablecoins and provides for the backdoor Centralized Bank Digital Currency. The Federal Reserve has been planning a CBDC for years and this will open the door to move you to a cashless society and into digital currency that can be weaponized against you by an authoritarian government controlling your ability to buy and sell. Do you actually trust your government to never do that to you? I don’t.

2. Anti-CBDC Surveillance State Act - I voted YES. This bill passed the House but we were told all week that it will not pass the Senate because the Senate does not have any path at all to get 60 votes to ban a CBDC. This bill prohibits Federal Reserve Banks from issuing a Central Bank Digital Currency. It’s a good bill and protects your money, but will die in the Senate. However, this should be people’s highest demand.

3. Clarity Act - I voted YES for self custody protections. This bill passed the House and will likely get some changes in the Senate then have come back to the House for another vote before it can be signed by the President and become law. This bill establishes a detailed regulatory framework for digital assets and allocates authority between the Commodity Futures Trading Commission (CFTC) and the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC). The most important thing that needs to remain is protecting people’s self custody of their digital currency. This is yet to be seen and should be demanded. I will vote NO when it comes back if self custody protections are taken out.

In 1971, we were taken off the gold standard to cash, which was a ridiculous decision and has weakened our dollar tremendously.

Now we are on the path to move from cash you can hold in your hand, hide from the government, and save for yourself and your family to a digital currency system where your ability to buy and sell will ultimately be held in digital accounts that you can not tangibly hold yet are at the will of those who control the banks and the government.

Name: Steil, Bryan
text:
🚨WISCONSIN ELECTION NEWS🚨
Yesterday, the Wisconsin Elections Commission voted on a substantial report to outline the former Madison City Clerk's failure to count nearly 200 ballots in the 2024 November election - HIGHLIGHTS BELOW🧵🧵🧵

Name: Steil, Bryan
text:
The report alleges that the former City Clerk “took actions that were contrary to law,” specifically:
- Wis. Stat. 7.15(1) – Clerk Supervision of Registration and Elections
- Wis. Stat. § 6.79(2)(a) – Early Printing of Poll Books
- Wis. Stat. §§ 6.88(1), (2) – Handling of Returned Absentee Ballots
- Wis. Stat. § 6.88(3) – Opening and Processing of Absentee Ballots
- Wis. Stat. § 7.51(5)(b) – Preparing the Municipal Board of Canvassers

Name: Steil, Bryan
text:
Lack of Robust Security Protections - According to WEC’s report:
The building used as a staging area for the City of Madison’s elections was found unlocked “on more than one occasion” and even had an “unauthorized person sleeping in the facility.”

Name: Steil, Bryan
text:
Knowledge of Uncounted Ballots - According to WEC’s report:
On November 12, the former City Clerk “had reason to know or suspect” that a bag discovered by election officials “contained live, uncounted ballots.” but action was not taken by the clerk until December

Name: Steil, Bryan
text:
Lack of Urgency - According to WEC’s report:
“The lack of action by the City Clerk with regard to the found ballots [was] astonishing. She demonstrated no urgency, let alone interest, in including those votes in the election tally ... That would have required the City Clerk to take the urgent action that the situation demanded. Instead, she went on vacation and, per her testimony, never inquired about them again until mid-December.”

Name: Steil, Bryan
text:
Lack of Leadership - According to WEC’s report:
“There was a complete lack of leadership in the City Clerk’s office. It was the job of the City Clerk to immediately take action once notified about the found ballots, and she did nothing. It was the responsibility of the Deputy Clerk to take action in her absence, and he did nothing. These ballots were treated as unimportant and a reconciliation nuisance, rather than as the essential part of our democracy they represent.”

Name: Steil, Bryan
text:
You can read WEC’s report yourself below
https://t.co/6ZgnbwDpuy

Name: Steil, Bryan
text:
These allegations, if true, outline a troubling pattern of neglect or disinterest by the former Clerk. 

Our election officials are entrusted to ensure votes are counted fairly, accurately, and on time. The actions of the former clerk and her refusal to take responsibility for the failures of her department directly undermine the faith and trust of Wisconsin voters. 

This can never be allowed to happen again.

Name: Harrigan, Pat
text:
94% of the amendments I introduced in @HASCRepublicans are now part of the NDAA.

Every one was written in my office, fought for in committee, and built to strengthen our national defense.

For our troops. For their mission. For our country.

Here’s what made it in ⬇️🧵

Name: Harrigan, Pat
text:
1. Banning adversary-owned businesses from U.S. military bases.

Companies tied to China, Russia, Iran, or North Korea shouldn’t be running shops for American servicemembers.

Name: Harrigan, Pat
text:
2. Closing a loophole for Chinese government-backed firms operating abroad.

If a company answers to Beijing, it shouldn’t be doing business with the Pentagon, no matter where it’s headquartered.

Name: Harrigan, Pat
text:
3. Phasing out Chinese pharmaceutical ingredients from the military supply chain.

We shouldn’t depend on the CCP for medicines used to treat American troops.

Name: Harrigan, Pat
text:
4. Powering military data centers with on-base nuclear energy.

Small modular reactors give our most sensitive systems 24/7 protection from grid failure or attack.

Name: Harrigan, Pat
text:
6. Advancing stealth drones that can survive in high-threat zones.

New designs focus on low visibility, acoustic reduction, and survivability in contested airspace.

Name: Harrigan, Pat
text:
5. Rebuilding America’s drone supply chain.

Too much of our unmanned aircraft technology is built overseas, this starts bringing that production home.

Name: Harrigan, Pat
text:
7. Using AI to speed up military construction.

Base projects are stuck in bureaucratic bottlenecks, AI helps streamline planning and approvals.

Name: Harrigan, Pat
text:
8. Standardizing battlefield battery systems with U.S.-made tech.

The current system is fragmented and foreign-sourced, this shifts us to reliable, modular, American-made power.

Name: Harrigan, Pat
text:
10. Testing smart fire controls on next-gen infantry rifles.

Before we field new weapon systems, we need to be sure they work under real combat conditions.

Name: Harrigan, Pat
text:
9. Expanding access to anonymous mental health care for troops.

Servicemembers deserve private, stigma-free ways to get support when they need it.

Name: Harrigan, Pat
text:
11. Funding development of long-range glide munitions.

These precision weapons are critical to keeping up with China, Russia, and modern threats.

Name: Harrigan, Pat
text:
13. Reviewing America’s gunpowder supply chain.

If we can’t produce our own ammunition components, we’re not ready for sustained conflict.

Name: Harrigan, Pat
text:
12. Adding drone defense training to Army basic training.

Every soldier should know how to identify and counter hostile drones from day one.

Name: Harrigan, Pat
text:
14. Reassessing U.S. troop posture in West Africa.

We’ve had forces deployed for years, this forces a hard look at the mission and the strategy.

Name: Harrigan, Pat
text:
15. Improving Army financial tracking.

The Pentagon still can’t pass a clean audit, this pushes better tools to follow where the money actually goes.

Name: Harrigan, Pat
text:
16. Preventing a return of the COVID vaccine mandate without congressional approval.

Major decisions about service requirements should go through Congress, not come from behind closed doors.

Name: Harrigan, Pat
text:
17. Including small nuclear reactors in DoD’s long-term energy planning.

Clean, resilient, on-base energy should be part of the future, not left off the roadmap.

Name: Sessions, Pete
text:
Proud to share that two of my key defense funding priorities were included in the FY26 Defense Appropriations bill, without increasing overall spending. This is a strategic shift in how existing funds are prioritized to better protect our national security.

SMART Hub research at @Baylor University will receive funding to advance cutting-edge RF and radar technologies. These innovations will enhance spectrum dominance on the battlefield and improve safety for our service members.

Additionally, funding was reallocated for a Department of Defense initiative to improve microelectronics security. This investment will fund a proof-of-concept for embedding unalterable security markings directly onto chips, marking a critical step toward full-spectrum semiconductor assurance across both our defense and critical infrastructure.

This bill demonstrates that we can make smart, future-focused investments in national defense by focusing resources where they’re needed most.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we recognize a Hometown Hero—someone whose impact on our community is lasting, profound, and deeply felt.
 
This week, we honor someone who has long embodied that title: Carla Reynolds. While she was named a Hometown Hero before, it only felt right—especially this week—to honor her once more.
 
This past weekend, we gathered for Unity Day, the event Carla built with love, vision, and purpose. It was moving, powerful, and unmistakably her. Though her physical presence was missing, her spirit filled every corner of that celebration.
 
Carla believed in the power of unity, not as a slogan, but as a way of life. Through Unity Day and her Boots on the Ground Foundation, she brought people together across every divide, fed families in crisis, and gave hope to those who felt unseen or unheard. She believed in meeting people where they are—and lifting them up with dignity and grace.
 
She also poured her heart into our young people, spotlighting Bucks County students who excelled in school, in service, and in sports—because, in her words, “Our kids need to know we see them.”
 
Carla made our community feel more whole, more connected, more compassionate, more human. Her life was a living example of what it means to love your neighbor. And though we said goodbye far too soon, we will continue to celebrate her, carry forward her mission, and ensure that Unity Day remains a tradition that reflects her values and vision.
 
To her daughter Tamara and all who loved her: thank you for sharing Carla with us—she will forever be our Hometown Hero.

Name: Cuellar, Henry
text:
Today, I held a press conference alongside Mayor Treviño to update the community on how the Department of Defense is supporting border security here in Laredo.
 
Last week, I toured one of the Stryker units with Mayor Treviño, Customs and Border Protection, and Army leadership to see firsthand how these armored vehicles equipped with thermal imaging and drone detection technology are helping strengthen our border security. These assets provide critical surveillance in the dense brush where illegal crossings often happen, giving Border Patrol real-time intelligence and allowing agents to respond more effectively and safely.
 
I also spoke with Major General Scott Naumann, Commander of Joint Task Force–Southwest Border, to hear directly what our troops need to succeed. The challenges we face are real and growing. Earlier this week, I was briefed on an alarming incident where an Army official was assaulted by an undocumented individual hiding in thick brush. Thankfully no one was injured, but these kinds of threats are increasing. Laredo now ranks among the top cities for cartel-operated drone activity, and the Rio Grande brush accounts for the vast majority of illegal crossings and concealment.
 
The Stryker units are already making an impact. Their cameras can detect movement as small as a mouse from over a mile away, helping Border Patrol focus resources where they are needed and deterring illegal crossings. Clearing overgrown vegetation is also critical to improving visibility and patrol mobility. The Stryker units are prepared to assist with clearing key zones in coordination with the International Boundary and Water Commission and local groups to ensure it’s done responsibly and transparently.
 
These vehicles remain on perimeter routes and use sensors, not weapons, to scan from a distance. They are not patrolling our streets or enforcing immigration law. This is a precision mission focused on deterring cartel drones, disrupting smuggling networks, and ensuring the safety of our frontline officers.
 
In Congress, I am working to fund river-road improvements, expand patrol access routes, remove Carrizo cane, and modernize federal law so Border Patrol and military units have the tools and protections they need.
 
I want to thank Mayor Treviño, Chief Muñoz, @DHSgov , @DeptofDefense , and our local law enforcement for working in lockstep to reducing cartel-drone incursions, illegal crossings, stash houses, and high-speed car chases. This unified effort across all levels of government is delivering results.
 
South Texas is strong and resilient. When we work together and lead with facts, not fear, we rise to any challenge. To every soldier, agent, and neighbor, thank you. I will keep fighting for you in Washington and listening to you here at home.

Without their expertise, who will sound the alarm?

This decision is reckless.

— Congressman Troy A. Carter, Sr.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On this day in history in 64, a massive fire swept through Emperor Nero’s Rome.

It raged for three days, completely destroying three of the city’s 14 districts, with only four left untouched. Hundreds were killed and thousands were left homeless. Legend says Nero played the fiddle while watching Rome burn.

Nero used the disaster to push his political agenda—he rebuilt the city with new architectural codes and blamed Christians for the fire, leading to their arrest, torture, and execution.

Name: Panetta, Jimmy
text:
I grew up in our Congressional District and have seen firsthand the growing issues with affordability that affect those of us who actually live here. That’s why affordable housing is my number one issue as the proud U.S. Representative for our home.  It’s why I introduced a legislative package as a member of the House Ways and Means Committee to help tackle this crisis from every angle: expanding tax credits to build more workforce housing, helping first-time homebuyers afford a down payment, freeing up existing housing stock, and co-leading the Rent Relief Act to put money back in renters' pockets when housing costs soar.

CA-19 was named the least affordable rental market in the U.S. To afford a modest two-bedroom, you’d need to earn $81.21/hour. That’s five full-time jobs at minimum wage. 

As your Federal Representative, I continue to fight the challenges that we face when it comes to affordability. I don’t just talk about it, I’m actually doing something about it to ensure that the federal government plays its part to ensure that living in CA-19 is more affordable.

Yesterday evening, a beautiful ceremony honored Claire “Reese” Manchaca—a Caney Creek graduate and gifted architecture student at UTSA—who tragically lost her life in the July 4th floods in Kerr County.

Reese had just completed her junior year and recently returned from studying abroad in Italy, where she passionately pursued her love of art, culture, and design. Last year, Reese was baptized and accepted Jesus Christ as her Lord and Savior.

She was camping with three of her closest friends—Joyce “JC” Badon, Ella Cahill, and Aidan Heartfield—when flash floods devastated the Texas Hill Country, claiming their lives and those of far too many others.

Name: McConnell, Mitch
text: Conservatives across America are honoring the life of Ed Feulner, founder and longest-serving President of the Heritage Foundation. Ed was a great man, and I am glad to have called him a friend through the years. Under Ed’s leadership, the Heritage Foundation was a bastion of Reagan conservatism and a steadfast ally in the fight for freedom and a strong defense. His dedication to promoting peace through strength at the end of the Cold War offers a particularly enduring lesson. Elaine and I are deeply saddened to learn of Ed’s passing, and we are thinking of his family during this time.

Name: Kaptur, Marcy
text: 🧵Last month, 325 Mayors, Tribal, and First Nation leaders committed to clean water, US-Canada relations, and climate resilience. They met to champion the Great Lakes and St. Lawrence Cities Initiative. Their efforts reflect the urgent needs of our Great Lakes communities. Thanks for your leadership!

Name: Kaptur, Marcy
text: Here are just some of the declarations and resolutions passed this year at the Great Lakes and St. Lawrence Cities Initiative Annual Meeting:

Name: Kaptur, Marcy
text: A resolution entitled “Advancing a Great Lakes-St. Lawrence Strong Response to the US-Canada Trade War,” highlighting the Cities Initiative’s strong opposition to blanket US tariffs on Canadian goods.

Name: Kaptur, Marcy
text: A declaration entitled “Preserving the US-Canada Relationship to Protect Our Prosperous Regional Economy and Our Precious Freshwater Resources,” that commits the Cities Initiative to working tirelessly to improve ties between the United States and Canada.

Name: Kaptur, Marcy
text: A resolution entitled “Upholding the Great Lakes-St. Lawrence River Basin Agreement and Compact,” reaffirming the Cities Initiative’s unwavering support for the Agreement and Compact – especially the ban on out-of-basin diversions.

Name: Kaptur, Marcy
text: A resolution entitled, "Reaffirming Support for the Great Lakes Water Quality Agreement," to express the Cities Initiative's ongoing support for the GLWQA and other transboundary efforts to maintain and improve water quality.

Name: Kaptur, Marcy
text: A resolution entitled “Protecting US Federal Funding to Combat Erosion and Flooding Across the Great Lakes and St. Lawrence River Basin,” calling on Congress to reject proposed funding cuts to NOAA programs that strengthen coastal resilience.

Name: Kaptur, Marcy
text: A resolution entitled “Maintaining Progress on Lead Service Line Replacement Through the Lead and Copper Rule Improvements,” encouraging Congress to reject any effort to repeal or weaken the Lead and Copper Rule Improvements.

Union troops initially pushed back the Confederates—but General Thomas “Stonewall” Jackson held firm, earning his famous nickname. The Confederates then seized Union artillery and launched a counterattack, forcing a Union retreat. The Confederate victory shattered hopes of a short war and proved it would be much more costly than anticipated.

Name: Suozzi, Thomas R.
text:
Never Forget the Vet!

Ninety-five years ago today, a Presidential Executive Order officially established the Veterans Administration to "consolidate and coordinate Government activities affecting war veterans." 

Since coming to Congress in 2017, one of my top priorities has always been to ensure that our veterans not only get the respect they deserve, but they also have access to the medical and social services they have earned. 

From pushing to see the demolition of hazardous and decaying structures at the VA in Northport to restoring historic fencing that surrounds the final resting place of our Nation’s veterans at the National Cemetery in Pinelawn, to securing posthumous military decorations and funding to support our living veterans, I promise to never “Forget the Vet.”

Whether you are raising a family, running a small business, operating a family farm, clocking in on the night shift, or living on a fixed income as a senior, the One Big Beautiful Bill was crafted to help you.

text:
💰In Wisconsin, families are expected to take home over $7,000 more each year.

According to the nonpartisan Joint Committee on Taxation, the biggest tax cuts will benefit Americans earning under $50,000 a year.

Name: Tiffany, Thomas P.
text:
🧑‍🧑‍🧒‍🧒The OBBB also raises the Child Tax Credit to $2,200 per child and establishes a $1,000 investment account for American newborns, helping give every child a head start.

It also supports working parents by expanding the Employer-Provided Child Care Credit.

Name: Tiffany, Thomas P.
text:
💵Beginning in 2025, tipped workers will be able to deduct tips from their taxable income—whether received in cash, by card, or through tip pooling.

Workers who log overtime will also be able to deduct their overtime pay from federal taxes.

Name: Tiffany, Thomas P.
text:
🚜For small businesses, the legislation makes permanent the Section 199A Qualified Business Income Deduction, which was set to expire at the end of 2025.

It also restores 100% bonus depreciation, allowing businesses to immediately deduct the full cost of new equipment.

Name: Tiffany, Thomas P.
text: 👵🏻Seniors benefit too. Thanks to the enhanced $6,000 standard deduction, nearly 9 in 10 Social Security recipients—more than 51 million Americans—will no longer pay federal taxes on their Social Security benefits.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: There are two rings in this circus. Most of the focus has been on Ring One: the badly abused Senate confirmation process, and our walkout as the majority broke committee rules to get Trump’s thug cleared through committee without answering questions.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text:
The race is on.

Republicans are moving today to Emil Bove’s nomination, rushing to get Trump’s thug cleared through the Senate while two Trump judges hold up the court contempt hearing that would bring out the facts hidden from us in Judiciary.

🧵

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: Not only did the majority let Bove dodge answering questions in Ring One, they gave pre-clearance with hand-waving about executive privileges Congress had never conceded apply against Congress’s powers of inquiry — greenlight to stonewall.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: With that signal, Bove never even properly asserted privileges. That would have met legal consternation about wrongful assertion. Having got the signal, he just refused, as “inappropriate,” or “not public” or “don’t recall.” That’s not how privilege works.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: Our questions focused on three instances of prosecutorial misconduct. In one, the “f*** you” instance, there was a well-corroborated whistleblower. That was also the instance where a judge had found probable cause for a contempt hearing.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: Then they broke the committee rules to ram the Trump thug through. When there’s an objection to a vote, the rules require a committee vote on moving to the vote. The chair just called the Bove vote, and the roll was called, even over a senator still speaking.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: That was the nasty business being performed in Ring One.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: They say that had been done before. No. Not like this. Only when Republicans used another rule to cancel a committee meeting, so we had to move to the vote; or when there had already been full debate in a previous meeting. This was a new low.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: Meanwhile, Ring Two is over at the Circuit Court of Appeals, where Trump judges Rao and Katsas, over objection, stopped the court hearing into Bove’s potential contempt in the deportation cases. In court, under oath, answers would be hard to dodge.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: The administrative stay procedure the Trump judges used usually only lasts days. Justice Barrett recently suggested a two-week administrative stay would be too long. This one has lasted three months, blocking the hearing that would have brought Bove’s misconduct to light.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: It’s hard to imagine that this isn’t a coordinated play, where one hand of the Trump operation gets an evidentiary hearing into a nominee’s misconduct blocked while another hand of the Trump operation gets the nominee rammed through confirmation.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: This stinks to high heaven.

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
Here's a hard but necessary truth:

For decades, our civil rights laws have been used not to prevent discrimination, but to enforce it.

Rather than protecting the equal rights of all citizens, the civil rights bureaucracy has become the enforcement arm of a new caste system.

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
Tomorrow, I'm leading a hearing on how we can forcibly dismantle the DEI regime.

For too long, our civil rights bureaucracy has aided and abetted discrimination.

It's time for lawbreakers to pay the price.

I'll be calling @HarmeetKDhillon and @GeneHamiltonUSA to testify. 🧵

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
This new system has gone by many names.

Today, it has found its most radical and extreme expression in the form of "diversity, equity, and inclusion" — or DEI.

DEI is not just illegal — it's a fraudulent and cynical doctrine, from top to bottom, built upon layers of lies.

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
And finally, it's not about "inclusion." It's about exclusion—of the competent, the qualified, the meritorious—when those people are members of the "wrong" race or sex.

Over the past few decades, this poisonous and brazenly illegal doctrine has transformed our institutions.

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
It's not about "diversity." It's about discrimination—a sustained campaign of collective punishment, wrapped in the rhetoric of social justice.

It's not about "equity." It's about power. They don't want to "level the playing field"—they want to elevate some groups over others.

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text: In many blue states, DEI is now entrenched in every level of government decision-making. At the federal level, it's produced a vast universe of civil service preferences, billions of dollars in taxpayer-funded minority-only grants, and open racial discrimination in contracting.

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text: In the universities, DEI has meant the abolition of merit. Even after the Supreme Court banned race-based admissions in 2023, elite schools like Harvard and Stanford just rebranded their quotas, embedding them in essay prompts and hiring policies rather than ending them outright.

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
In the corporate world, DEI has meant hiring and promotion not on the basis of competence, but on the basis of race and sex—a world where one’s place in the new caste system determines who rises and who falls.
https://t.co/K3TvFtltEg

Name: Pelosi, Nancy
text:
The crimes of Jeffrey Epstein and his enablers shattered countless lives and exposed a vast system of exploitation and violence against women and girls.

Today, I am proud to join as a cosponsor of the Epstein Files Transparency Act — a vital step toward truth and accountability in the face of unspeakable abuse. With this resolution, we declare unequivocally that violence against women will not be ignored.  

For years, Epstein’s victims — many of them just children when they were abused — have waited for justice, often in silence and in pain. 

They deserve answers. They deserve dignity. And they deserve action from their government. 

That is why it is especially shameful that Speaker Johnson has shut down the House of Representatives for the summer to avoid a vote on this resolution. 

To block transparency in this manner is not only an abdication of duty — it is a profound insult to the victims who have carried the burden of this trauma for decades.  

The American people deserve to know the full extent of who was involved with Epstein and all of them must be held accountable — no matter how powerful. 

As we pursue accountability, we must respect the voices and privacy of the survivors to honor their courage, protect their dignity, and ensure that the full truth comes to light. 

Justice delayed is justice denied. The American people — and the survivors — deserve better.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
At today’s @WaysandMeansGOP hearing, I spoke about the critical need to protect and strengthen Medicare Advantage—a program that now covers over half of all seniors on Medicare.

In Pennsylvania, MA beneficiaries save over $3,000 a year on average and experience 70% fewer hospital readmissions compared to traditional Medicare.

I have been, and will continue to be, firm in my efforts to protect and improve essential programs like Medicare Advantage because they deliver real results for our seniors.

Today, I asked Alignment Health CEO Dawn Maroney how integrated care is improving patient outcomes, and Dr. Brian Miller how we can reduce administrative burdens like prior authorization that delay care and drain provider resources.

The evidence is undeniable: Medicare Advantage is essential, it works, and it can and must be strengthened—not sidelined.

Name: Sullivan, Dan
text:
The PRO Vets Act has passed the House! My legislation passed the Senate earlier this month and will now go to the President to be signed into law. 

I introduced this legislation after a shocking budget debacle at the VA under the Biden administration: a supposed multi-billion-dollar budget shortfall in mid-2024 followed by a multi-billion-dollar surplus two months later. The PRO Vets Act works to re-establish accountability at the VA by mandating quarterly, in-person budget reports to Congress and withholding bonuses for senior VA and Office of Management and Budget (OMB) personnel if there are future financial shortfalls.

As a member of @SVACGOP, I will continue working closely with @secvetaffairs Doug Collins who supports greater accountability, to hold the VA to the high standards the American people expect and to ensure our veterans are receiving the care and benefits they have earned.
